Bank Churn Prediction¶

Problem Statement

Context¶

Businesses like banks which provide service have to worry about problem of 'Customer Churn' i.e. customers leaving and joining another service provider. It is important to understand which aspects of the service influence a customer's decision in this regard. Management can concentrate efforts on improvement of service, keeping in mind these priorities.

Objective¶

You as a Data scientist with the bank need to build a neural network based classifier that can determine whether a customer will leave the bank or not in the next 6 months.

Data Dictionary:¶

  • CustomerId: Unique ID which is assigned to each customer

  • Surname: Last name of the customer

  • CreditScore: It defines the credit history of the customer.

  • Geography: A customer’s location

  • Gender: It defines the Gender of the customer

  • Age: Age of the customer

  • Tenure: Number of years for which the customer has been with the bank

  • NumOfProducts: refers to the number of products that a customer has purchased through the bank.

  • Balance: Account balance

  • HasCrCard: It is a categorical variable which decides whether the customer has credit card or not.

  • EstimatedSalary: Estimated salary

  • isActiveMember: Is is a categorical variable which decides whether the customer is active member of the bank or not ( Active member in the sense, using bank products regularly, making transactions etc )

  • Exited : whether or not the customer left the bank within six month. It can take two values 0=No ( Customer did not leave the bank ) 1=Yes ( Customer left the bank )

# function to plot a boxplot and a histogram along the same scale.


def histogram_boxplot(data, feature, figsize=(12, 7), kde=False, bins=None):
    """
    Boxplot and histogram combined

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    figsize: size of figure (default (12,7))
    kde: whether to the show density curve (default False)
    bins: number of bins for histogram (default None)
    """
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2,  # Number of rows of the subplot grid= 2
        sharex=True,  # x-axis will be shared among all subplots
        gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},
        figsize=figsize,
    )  # creating the 2 subplots
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data, x=feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color="violet"
    )  # boxplot will be created and a triangle will indicate the mean value of the column
    sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins, palette="winter"
    ) if bins else sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2
    )  # For histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].mean(), color="green", linestyle="--"
    )  # Add mean to the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].median(), color="black", linestyle="-"
    )  # Add median to the histogram

# function to create labeled barplots


def labeled_barplot(data, feature, perc=False, n=None):
    """
    Barplot with percentage at the top

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    perc: whether to display percentages instead of count (default is False)
    n: displays the top n category levels (default is None, i.e., display all levels)
    """

    total = len(data[feature])  # length of the column
    count = data[feature].nunique()
    if n is None:
        plt.figure(figsize=(count + 1, 5))
    else:
        plt.figure(figsize=(n + 1, 5))

    plt.xticks(rotation=90, fontsize=15)
    ax = sns.countplot(
        data=data,
        x=feature,
        palette="Paired",
        order=data[feature].value_counts().index[:n].sort_values(),
    )

    for p in ax.patches:
        if perc == True:
            label = "{:.1f}%".format(
                100 * p.get_height() / total
            )  # percentage of each class of the category
        else:
            label = p.get_height()  # count of each level of the category

        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2  # width of the plot
        y = p.get_height()  # height of the plot

        ax.annotate(
            label,
            (x, y),
            ha="center",
            va="center",
            size=12,
            xytext=(0, 5),
            textcoords="offset points",
        )  # annotate the percentage

    plt.show()  # show the plot

# function to plot stacked bar chart

def stacked_barplot(data, predictor, target):
    """
    Print the category counts and plot a stacked bar chart

    data: dataframe
    predictor: independent variable
    target: target variable
    """
    count = data[predictor].nunique()
    sorter = data[target].value_counts().index[-1]
    tab1 = pd.crosstab(data[predictor], data[target], margins=True).sort_values(
        by=sorter, ascending=False
    )
    print(tab1)
    print("-" * 120)
    tab = pd.crosstab(data[predictor], data[target], normalize="index").sort_values(
        by=sorter, ascending=False
    )
    tab.plot(kind="bar", stacked=True, figsize=(count + 1, 5))
    plt.legend(
        loc="lower left", frameon=False,
    )
    plt.legend(loc="upper left", bbox_to_anchor=(1, 1))
    plt.show()

### Function to plot distributions

def distribution_plot_wrt_target(data, predictor, target):

    fig, axs = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(12, 10))

    target_uniq = data[target].unique()

    axs[0, 0].set_title("Distribution of target for target=" + str(target_uniq[0]))
    sns.histplot(
        data=data[data[target] == target_uniq[0]],
        x=predictor,
        kde=True,
        ax=axs[0, 0],
        color="teal",
    )

    axs[0, 1].set_title("Distribution of target for target=" + str(target_uniq[1]))
    sns.histplot(
        data=data[data[target] == target_uniq[1]],
        x=predictor,
        kde=True,
        ax=axs[0, 1],
        color="orange",
    )

    axs[1, 0].set_title("Boxplot w.r.t target")
    sns.boxplot(data=data, x=target, y=predictor, ax=axs[1, 0], palette="gist_rainbow")

    axs[1, 1].set_title("Boxplot (without outliers) w.r.t target")
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data,
        x=target,
        y=predictor,
        ax=axs[1, 1],
        showfliers=False,
        palette="gist_rainbow",
    )

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

Outlier Detection¶

In [ ]:
# checking for outliers in the dataset.
numeric_data = df.select_dtypes(include=['int64', 'float64'])
Q1 = numeric_data.quantile(0.25)  # The 25th percentile.
Q3 = numeric_data.quantile(0.75)  # The 75th percentile.

IQR = Q3 - Q1           # Inter Quantile Range (75th perentile - 25th percentile)

lower = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR  # Finding the lower bounds for all values. All values outside these bounds are outliers.
upper = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR  # Finding the upper bounds for all values. All values outside these bounds are outliers.

Model Building

Model Evaluation Criterion¶

Below parameters needs to be considered for model building -

Possible Wrong Predictions:

False Positive (FP): Predicting a customer will exit when they actually stay. False Negative (FN): Predicting a customer will stay when they actually exit. Which Case is More Important?

False Negatives (FN) are more critical: Predicting a customer will stay but they actually exit is problematic. This misjudgment can lead to a loss for the bank since these customers will not receive any retention efforts or incentives to stay. How to Minimize Loss from False Negatives?

Focusing on Reducing False Negatives:

Goal: Minimize FN, which means accurately identifying customers who are likely to leave. Why? because , If the bank can correctly identify these potential churners, it can take proactive measures to retain them.

Strategy to Reduce False Negatives:

Maximize Recall:

Definition: Recall is the ability of the model to identify all relevant instances (i.e., correctly predicting exiting customers). Impact: Higher recall means fewer False Negatives (FN), improving the bank’s ability to retain at-risk customers. Focus on True Positives: Ensuring the model accurately identifies customers who are truly at risk of leaving (Class 1). By prioritizing recall, the bank can more effectively target and retain customers who are likely to churn, thereby reducing potential losses.

In [ ]:
def make_confusion_matrix(actual_targets, predicted_targets):
    """
    To plot the confusion_matrix with percentages

    actual_targets: actual target (dependent) variable values
    predicted_targets: predicted target (dependent) variable values
    """
    cm = confusion_matrix(actual_targets, predicted_targets)
    labels = np.asarray(
        [
            ["{0:0.0f}".format(item) + "\n{0:.2%}".format(item / cm.flatten().sum())]
            for item in cm.flatten()
        ]
    ).reshape(cm.shape[0], cm.shape[1])

    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=labels, fmt="")
    plt.ylabel("True label")
    plt.xlabel("Predicted label")

Observations :

Neural Network with SGD Optimizer

Recall Analysis:

The model has a high recall for Class 0 (Non-Churners) in both training (0.96) and validation (0.96) datasets, indicating it is very good at correctly identifying non-churners. The recall for Class 1 (Churners) is lower in both training (0.43) and validation (0.42) datasets. This indicates the model struggles to correctly identify churners, potentially missing many actual churners (false negatives).

  • The dataset is imbalanced, with significantly more non-churners. This is reflected in the model's higher performance in predicting non-churners versus churners.

  • Approximately 11% of customers are leaving without the bank making any attempt to intervene.

Improving Churner Detection:

1.Focus on Recall for Class 1 (Churners):

Since reducing churn is critical, improving the recall for churners should be a priority to capture more of those who are likely to leave.

2.Balance Data:

Use techniques like SMOTE to balance the training data more effectively. This can help the model learn to identify churners better.

3.Adjust Model Parameters:

Fine-tuning hyperparameters, such as increasing the number of neurons or adding layers, can help improve performance.

4.Use Advanced Models:

Consider more sophisticated models or ensemble methods that might better handle the complexity of the data.

5.Threshold Adjustment:

Changing the decision threshold could help balance precision and recall for the minority class.

print('Best Threshold=%f, G-Mean=%.3f' % (thresholds1[ix], gmeans1[ix]))

Neural Network model with Adam Optimizer

Recall Analysis for Training Data:

1.Class 0 (Non-Churners): The recall is 0.83, indicating the model correctly identifies 83% of non-churning customers. Given that this class is the majority, the model performs well but could still improve.

2.Class 1 (Churners): The recall is 0.85, showing that the model captures 85% of actual churners. This is a strong recall rate for churners, suggesting the model is good at identifying those likely to leave.

3.Macro Average Recall: 0.84, indicating a balanced ability to detect both classes correctly.

Recall Analysis for Validation Data:

1.Class 0 (Non-Churners): The recall is 0.81, slightly lower than in training, which suggests some degradation in model performance on unseen data for this class.

2.Class 1 (Churners): The recall is 0.75, also lower than in training. This drop indicates the model misses 25% of the churners in the validation set, which could be critical for business decisions.

3.Macro Average Recall: 0.78, showing a drop from the training set. This might indicate some overfitting to the training data or that the validation data presents slightly different characteristics.

Overall Performance Evaluation:

Training Set: High recall for churners (0.85) indicates the model learns well from the training data to detect churn. This is critical for identifying most of the churners and taking preventive actions. Validation Set: While recall for churners (0.75) is still reasonable, the drop from the training set suggests the model's generalization to new data could be improved.

Improve Recall for Churners:

Further fine-tuning of the model to enhance recall for Class 1 (churners) is essential. Consider techniques like ensemble methods, cost-sensitive learning, or adjusting class weights.

1.Threshold Adjustment: Experimenting with different decision thresholds could optimize the recall-precision trade-off for churners. Enhance Model Generalization:

2.Reducing the gap between training and validation performance is crucial. Techniques such as cross-validation, regularization, and dropout adjustments can help.

3.Feature Engineering: Investigate additional features or interactions that may help the model better capture the factors leading to churn. Balance Precision and Recall:

4.While improving recall is important for churn prediction, maintaining a balance with precision ensures the model doesn't generate too many false positives. This balance is crucial for actionable insights and effective business strategies.

5.Practical Business Actions: Using the model's predictions, focus retention efforts on customers flagged as potential churners, and continuously refine the model with new data to adapt to changing customer behaviors.

Observation :

Neural Network with Adam Optimizer and Dropout

Recall Analysis for Training Data:

Class 0 (Non-Churners): The recall is 0.81, indicating the model correctly identifies 81% of non-churning customers. Given that this class is the majority, the model performs reasonably well.

Class 1 (Churners): The recall is 0.88, showing that the model captures 88% of actual churners. This is a high recall rate for churners, suggesting the model is very effective at identifying those likely to leave.

Macro Average Recall: 0.84, reflecting a balanced ability to detect both classes correctly, with a slight emphasis on the minority class (churners) due to its critical business impact.

Recall Analysis for Validation Data:

Class 0 (Non-Churners): The recall is 0.79, slightly lower than in training, indicating some degradation in model performance on unseen data for this class.

Class 1 (Churners): The recall is 0.76, also lower than in training. This drop suggests the model misses 24% of the churners in the validation set, which could be critical for business decisions.

Macro Average Recall: 0.78, showing a drop from the training set. This might indicate some overfitting to the training data or that the validation data presents slightly different characteristics.

Overall Performance Evaluation:

Training Set: The high recall for churners (0.88) indicates the model learns well from the training data to detect churn. This is critical for identifying most of the churners and taking preventive actions. Validation Set: The recall for churners (0.76) remains relatively strong, but the drop from the training set indicates potential overfitting or data distribution differences. Improving generalization is key.

Conclusions and Recommendations: Improve Recall for Churners by fine tuning model with ensemble methods, adjusting class weights, applying cost sensitive learning, apply various decision thresholds to optimize recall-precision trade off for churners.

  1. Enhance Model Generalization:Reducing the gap between training and validation performance with Techniques such as cross-validation, regularization, and dropout adjustments can help.

  2. Feature Engineering: Investigate additional features or interactions that may help the model better capture the factors leading to churn. Analyzing feature importance and potential non-linear relationships could be beneficial.

Balance Precision and Recall:

While improving recall is crucial for churn prediction, maintaining a balance with precision ensures the model doesn't generate too many false positives. This balance is vital for actionable insights and effective business strategies.

Practical Business Actions:

Using the model's predictions, focus retention efforts on customers flagged as potential churners, and continuously refine the model with new data to adapt to changing customer behaviors.

# Defining function to create and compile ANN.
def create_model(dropout_rate=0.1,lr=0.001,layer_1=64,layer_2=32,batch_size=40):
    np.random.seed(1337)
    #Initializing the neural network
    model3 = Sequential()
    # This adds the input layer (by specifying input dimension).
    model3.add(Dense(layer_1,activation='relu',input_dim = X_train.shape[1]))
    # Adding dropout.
    model3.add(Dropout(0.5))
    # Adding the hidden layer.
    model3.add(Dense(layer_2,activation='relu'))
    # Adding the output layer.
    model3.add(Dense(1, activation='sigmoid'))
    # Adding Adam initializer.
    optimizer = tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=lr)
    # Compiling with Adam optimizer and binary cross entropy loss function.
    model3.compile(optimizer = optimizer,loss = 'binary_crossentropy', metrics = [keras.metrics.Recall()])
    return model3

Observations : Neural Network with Balanced Data (by applying SMOTE),Adam Optimizer and Dropout

Recall Analysis:

Training Data: Non-Churners (Class 0): The model has a high recall of 89%, meaning it correctly identifies 89% of the non-churning customers. This indicates the model is highly effective in capturing non-churners. Churners (Class 1): The recall for churners is 64%, indicating the model correctly identifies 64% of the customers who churn. This suggests a moderate ability to detect churners during training.

Validation Data: Non-Churners (Class 0): Recall remains high at 89%, showing consistent performance in identifying non-churners on unseen data. Churners (Class 1): Recall is 63%, slightly lower than in training but still within a reasonable range. This indicates the model’s capacity to generalize for churners is stable but could be improved.

Accuracy and Averages:

1.Training Data: The model achieves an accuracy of 0.77, meaning it correctly predicts 77% of the instances. The macro and weighted averages show balanced performance across both classes.

2.Validation Data: Accuracy improves to 0.84, indicating that 84% of predictions are correct. The weighted average F1-Score of 0.84 suggests the model is robust in general, but with room for improvement in churn predictions.

Conclusions and Recommendations:

1.Focus on Balanced Performance : The goal is to achieve a better balance between precision and recall for churners, ensuring that the model not only captures true churners effectively but also minimizes the number of false alarms (non-churners predicted as churners).

2.Evaluate Business Impact: From a business perspective, the priority should be reducing false negatives (missed churners), even at the cost of accepting more false positives. This approach will help retain customers more effectively, aligning with business goals.

3.Consider Advanced Architectures: Exploring deeper neural network architectures or incorporating techniques like dropout and batch normalization could enhance the model's ability to capture complex patterns and improve performance for the minority class (churners).

4.Regularization and Hyperparameter Tuning: Applying regularization techniques and tuning hyperparameters helps in reducing overfitting, leading to better generalization and improved recall and precision metrics for churners.

  • This model performs slightly less improved than the previous model. Recall is down by 0.63 with accuracy of 84% on validation set. Results in approx 7% of customers leaving without the bank attempting to intervene.

  • Accuracy: The overall accuracy (0.74) indicates the model is classifying correctly most of the time (74%).

  • Precision (Class 0): The model is very precise (0.93) in identifying negative examples (class 0). This means when it predicts something as negative, it's usually correct.

  • Recall (Class 1): The model struggles with recall (0.78) for positive examples (class 1). This means it misses a significant portion (22%) of actual positives.

  • Precision (Class 1): The precision (0.42) for positive examples is also low. This indicates that out of the examples it predicts as positive, only 42% are truly positive. There are many false positives.

Actionable Insights:

Focus on Class 1: Given the importance of correctly classifying positive examples (class 1), prioritize improving recall and precision for this class. Techniques like oversampling or undersampling the training data can help address class imbalance, on further model performance, as & when needed.

Cost-Sensitive Learning: If misclassifying positive examples is more critical than misclassifying negatives, considering cost-sensitive learning we can assign a higher cost to misclassifying class 1 during training.

Hyperparameter Tuning: Experiment with different hyperparameters of neural network architecture (e.g., number of layers, learning rate) to see if it improves performance on class 1.

Alternative Metrics: Depending on the specific problem, using metrics like F1-score that considers both precision and recall might be more informative than just accuracy.
